        <div class="hero">
            <div class="about">
                <p class="hero-text">Data Encryption Standard (DES) is a symmetric-key algorithm for encrypting digital data. It works on 64-bit blocks of plaintext and transforms them into 64-bit blocks of ciphertext using a 56-bit secret key. DES uses a series of permutations
                    and substitutions arranged in a Feistel network over 16 rounds, making the data secure by mixing the key with the plaintext in multiple steps.</p>

                <One class="hero-text">One of the simplest modes of using DES is Electronic Codebook (ECB). In ECB mode, the plaintext is split into fixed-size blocks, and each block is encrypted independently with the same key. While this makes ECB easy to implement and efficient,
                    it also has a weakness: identical plaintext blocks produce identical ciphertext blocks, which can reveal patterns in the data. Because of this, ECB is best for short or pattern-free data, but not recommended for sensitive or large-scale
                    encryption.</p>
            </div>

